              <tr>
                <td bgcolor="#000000" background="images/forum-cell.gif" colspan="2" align="center"><b><font face="arial" size="2" color="#FFFFFF">T O P I C&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;R E V I E W</font></b></td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td bgcolor="#0A0634" valign="top" width="100" nowrap><font color="#FFFFFF" face="arial" size="2"><b>Neorott</b></font></td>
                <td bgcolor="#0A0634" valign="top" width="100%"><font color="#FFFFFF" face="arial" size="2"><small>Posted&nbsp;-&nbsp;04/07/2003&nbsp;: 1:19:57 PM</small><hr size="2"><span class="spnMessageText"> Can we get this stickied?<br /><br />Some in the forum may not like this post. But I firmly believe it's time for Necros to start putting an end to druid rudeness and bad behavior. <i><font color="orange">If for anything else, our own self defense.</font id="orange"></i><br />[Background]<br />Last night I ran into another very nice Necromancer in TD who was very upset at how he had been treated by druids.<br /><br />"They take everything with no regard to anyone else in the zone", he said.<br /><br />So I told him a few tricks to help him out the next time he has this problem. He thanked me, we went about sharing the spawns as Necros tend to do.<br /><br />So with that, I give you, <font color="yellow">A Necros Guide to killing a druid.</font id="yellow"> <img src="images/azumaan.gif" border="0" alt="" title="" align="middle" /><br /><br />[Killing him psychologically]<br />1) Never use /shout or /ooc to confront a druid. This is druid behavior and is considered the mark of loser.<br /><br />2) If you can control your temper, never respond to the dog at all. This is very frustrating to most dogs. They want attention. If you simply act then ignore all their attempts to get your attention, you will make them cry.<br /><br />You will know it's working when they track you down and stand infront of you. Sometimes they repeatidly inspect you. If they do this, you know you've won. <br /><br />3)Denying the dog what they came for. This is accomplished in several ways. <br />3a) Chain pulling mobs in the dogs area.<br />3b) Wait till the dog has pulled 4 mobs, then cast Fear on 2 of them. Thus making him use more mana. (Besure to FD after the second Fear to clear aggro.)<br />3c) Wait till the dog has pulled 4 mobs and Root one of them. If the dog tries dot the rooted mob, cast annul magic and let it chase him.<br /><br />[killing him physically]<br />1)Druids can be tough to kill. However it can be accomplised if you're a little creative. Everyone thinks about FD pulling, but do you FD the correct way?<br /><br />1a) In OOT at SeaFury island, when you FD a train on the druid, do you make sure you took the time to round up some goblins and specters in order to give your train the maximum chance to stun and thus kill the offending druid? The Darkelf pirate is very good at doing this too.<br /><br />1b) Timing is everything. Wait until the druid already has a quad snared, then FD train the druid from behind. This gives you the added bonus that his quad catches up and pounds the dog too.<br /><br />1c) Cancel magic line is your friend. A druid has a routine the dog goes through with each quad. <font color="yellow">a)</font id="yellow"> Pull 4 mobs. <font color="yellow">b)</font id="yellow"> Circle the 4 mobs until they are in a tight circle. <font color="yellow">c)</font id="yellow">Run far enough way so that the dog has sufficient time to cast an AoE. Wait till Rover is done getting his tight circle, then starts the AoE run. When Rover turns to run, cast Annul magic on one of the mobs.<br /><br />He might not catch on that you're the one messing with his furry hide. It could be a casting mob off some place doing it. This gives great entertainment for hours. Or however long it takes rin tin tin to figure it out..<br /><br />2) In a dungeon, wait till Hairypaws_110 pulls his mob, cast annul magic, then immediately cast Fear, then FD. The Feared mob will aggro everything else in the dungeon with only one player on it's aggro list. This is truely fun to watch. <img src="images/azumaan.gif" border="0" alt="" title="" align="middle" /><br /><br />3) Gather up as many mobs as you can, run past WolfieFeet_25, not up too, run past. when the mobs are on top of the offending druid, FD. Press F9 a couple times and watch the fun. Don't respond to Fuzzy insuing /tell barage.<br /><br />[Defense]<br />1) You must be ready for anything HairyFeet_45 is going to throw at you. The best way is to be on your guard.<br /><font color="yellow">1a)</font id="yellow"> If he tries to train you. Besure to back your pet off the mob he's fighting and FD quickly. When Rover tries to deal with this train, refer to <font color="yellow">[killing him physically]</font id="yellow"> section above.<br /><br />2) If Treehugger_478 roots your mob inorder to kill your pet, common evil druid tactic, there are several things you can do.<br /><font color="yellow">2a)</font id="yellow"> Cast Annul magic on the mob, click /pet get lost, and FD. Then let the dr00d deal with the mob. Continuing to Annul magic when needed to make it as hard as possible on Rover.<br /><br /><font color="yellow">2b)</font id="yellow"> Burn the mob down.<br /><br />[conclusion]<br />By all means, please add to this list anything I missed as we all learn from the experience of others.<br /><br />-Neo</span></font></td>
              </tr>
